<p>Japan’s new prime minister, Sanae Takaichi, said Japan wants constructive relations with China and that its Taiwan stance remains unchanged, after Beijing demanded she retract remarks suggesting a Taiwan conflict could be deemed a survival-threatening situation under Japan’s security laws [scmp.com#1][thehindu.com#1][nytimes.com#1]. China has escalated countermeasures by suspending travel and seafood purchases from Japan [lemonde.fr#1], including a suspension of seafood imports [firstpost.com#1]. Travel has been disrupted: nearly half a million China-to-Japan air tickets were recently canceled and some Hong Kong airlines are offering refunds or flexible changes [scmp.com#2]. Separately, about 30% of 1.44 million China-to-Japan trips planned for next month have been canceled, with potential visitor-spending losses estimated around $1.2 billion [firstpost.com#2].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/aZaDciFFYZcO-eofPSZExnLfhRq75SmFcXVTXp_3g36jmNWSaC-870MTWrYDMxzpiAYZiisfNl2AS_u0VwOny3HPCnvqJMnuH6mTk4dKRaPapBeGrwd9KDG83_fkqS2kCgKSKLnhX2nfo_QsKBQV4niJUJPaiZKZP4IcFtHoPcb7cYC27g' alt='Japan’s Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi arrives to meet China’s Xi Jinping in Gyeongju, South Korea, in October.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Takaichi said Japan has been consistent on Taiwan, seeks constructive ties with Beijing, and that Tokyo would make a comprehensive judgment based on available information regarding any survival-threatening situation; she did not retract her earlier remarks [scmp.com#1][thehindu.com#1][nytimes.com#1]</li><li>Beijing responded by suspending travel to Japan and halting seafood purchases as pressure over Tokyo’s Taiwan-related statements [lemonde.fr#1][firstpost.com#1]</li><li>Tourism disruption includes nearly 500,000 canceled China–Japan air tickets, advisories from mainland and Hong Kong authorities, and airlines offering refunds or flexible changes [scmp.com#2]</li><li>Around 30% of 1.44 million planned China-to-Japan trips for next month have been canceled, with potential visitor-spending losses estimated at about $1.2 billion [firstpost.com#2]</li><li>Takaichi said that she and President Xi last month confirmed the broad direction of comprehensively advancing strategic ties, indicating ongoing communication channels [thehindu.com#1]</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Japan (Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi): Japan’s Taiwan stance is unchanged; Tokyo seeks constructive ties with China and will judge any potential survival-threatening scenario based on comprehensive information [scmp.com#1][thehindu.com#1] (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3333718/japanese-leader-says-she-wants-better-ties-china-doesnt-withdraw-taiwan-comments'>SCMP; The Hindu</a>)</li><li>China: Beijing demanded a retraction of Takaichi’s remarks and escalated pressure by suspending travel and seafood purchases from Japan [lemonde.fr#1][firstpost.com#1] (<a href='https://www.lemonde.fr/en/international/article/2025/11/21/china-ramps-up-retaliatory-measures-against-japan-suspending-travel-and-seafood-purchases_6747692_4.html'>Le Monde; Firstpost</a>)</li><li>Hong Kong travel authorities and airlines: Authorities cautioned against travel to Japan; some airlines offered refunds or flexible arrangements [scmp.com#2] (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/society/article/3333665/how-china-japan-spat-disrupting-travel-and-what-it-means-hong-kong'>SCMP</a>)</li><li>Le Monde analysis: China’s measures seek to pressure Tokyo to reverse its stance and deter other governments from expressing support for Taiwan [lemonde.fr#1] (<a href='https://www.lemonde.fr/en/international/article/2025/11/21/china-ramps-up-retaliatory-measures-against-japan-suspending-travel-and-seafood-purchases_6747692_4.html'>Le Monde</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3333718/japanese-leader-says-she-wants-better-ties-china-doesnt-withdraw-taiwan-comments'>Japan PM says she want